03946nam a22005655i 9780804793025DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202014cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047930257 a10.1515/97808047930252doi  a(DE-B1597)564968  a(OCoLC)1198930675  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aB2430 7aPHI0270002bisacsh04a1941 aLüdemann, Susanne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitics of Deconstruction :bA New Introduction to Jacques Derrida /cSusanne Lüdemann. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Derrida's Legacy -- tFirst Approach: Generations, Genealogies, Translations, and Contexts -- tSecond Approach: The Metaphysics of Presence and the Deconstruction of Logocentrism -- tThird Approach: There Are "Undeconstructibles" (Are There?) -- tFourth Approach: Deconstruction and Democracy -- tEpilogue: Deconstruction in America / America in Deconstruction -- tAppendix: Biography of Jacques Derrida -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe book offers a new introduction to Jacques Derrida and to Deconstruction as an important strand of Continental Philosophy. From his early writings on phenomenology and linguistics to his later meditations on war, terrorism, and justice, Jacques Derrida (1930-2004) achieved prominence on an international scale by addressing as many different audiences as he did topics. Yet despite widespread acclamation, his work has never been considered easy. Rendering accessible debates that marked more than four decades of engagement and inquiry, Susanne Lüdemann traces connections between the philosopher's own texts and those of his many interlocutors, past and present. Unlike conventional introductions, Politics of Deconstruction offers a number of personal approaches to reading Derrida and invites readers to find their own. Emphasizing the relationship between philosophy and politics, it shows that, with Deconstruction, there is much more at stake than an "academic" discussion, for Derrida's work deals with all the burning political and intellectual challenges of our time. The author's own professional experience in both the United States and in Europe, which particularly inform her chapter on Derrida's reception in the United States, opens a unique perspective on a unique thinker, one that rewards specialists and newcomers alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCriticism. 0aDeconstruction. 4aJacques Derrida. 4acontinental philosophy. 4acritique of metaphysics. 4adeconstruction. 4apoststructuralism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479302540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804793025423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804793025.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles